Morendil wrote:
>>In principle I am against any legislation of a Player's Nomicality -
our analogue to nationality.<<

I must admit I'm a little surprized to hear you, of all players, say
that after the anti-war campaigning you have done. If it wasn't for
the "nomicality" of the players involved, the whole enterprize you
disliked could hardly have been considered an "invasion" or a "war
effort" at all, could it? - maybe as the malicious action of a player,
or a group of players.

But the danger of players joining a Nomic with bad intentions has
nothing to do with inter-nomic relations. It is present because (and
as long as) nomics run via open mailing lists or other open systems
that are hard to protect against such attacks. (Of course this is an
interesting problem, too: how to organize an immigration policy that
protects you from evildoers, but does not keep people from joining. In
Agora the senate provides for that, I think),

Morendil:
>>I wouldn't like any restriction, however benign in intent, on my
rights to circulate freely within the Nomic Community.<<

My idea is not to restrict registrations in any way, just to force
people to publish their nomic memberships. It would only allow
individual nomics to introduce such restrictions internally. But they
can do that already, and why shouldn't they be allowed to do it?

I don't see in which way my idea conflicts with your goal that

>>...a Nomic should be free to adopt any kind of immigration policy it
likes, provided naturally that the basic rights of the Players are
respected by its legislation.
If Rishon wants to subject immigrant Players to a detailed questionnaire,
so be it - I certainly don't approve, but neither do I think such a move
would be unfounded in light of recent events. ;)<<

Morendil:
>>Note though that IN Points are really less than exciting - member
Nomics seem to care little for them.<<

I don't mind that too much - it's just like real life, isn't it? Some
nations can be condemned by UN resolutions over and over again, but
they just don't care. And not all of them automatically loose their
reputation or status, either, if they are interresting or powerful
enough to ignore the UN's "sanctions".

I think that's a very interesting part of international politics - you
do want a forum for exchange, and you do want to fix some elementary
standards and a kind of code of conduct for all, but the means to
enforce such standards are very limited indeed - basically limited to
persuasion and moral pressure. Why should Internomic be different?

Kolja A.

