Here is the version that Blob posted on 9 June. I don't know whether it
is the most current version.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

PROTO: Plots v0.2

------------

This is a combined effort by Antimatter and myself, at creating some form
of economy around here. The basic aim is the same as my earlier Jobs 
proto - to encourage Players to specialise in the production of one of
our major currencies - VTs, P-Notes or Indulgences - and then trade their
excess for other currencies.

The concept we are working with is that of land ownership and building
various structures on your land, to produce the various commodities. A
unit of land is a Plot. Each player starts with 3 of these, but they can
be traded. On a Plot, a player can build a Structure. Every week, a
Structure produces a certain amount of a given currency, depending on its
type. Houses produce P-Notes, Farms produce VTs, Churches (indirectly)
produce Indulgences, there are also Mines, which produce a new currency
call Materials, which is necessary for creating & maintaining Structures.

A player must pay monthly upkeep on eir Structures, or else they fall 
apart. Upkeep is paid in Materials, and is 1 Mt/month for each Structure,
plus 1 extra Mt for each type of Structure owned. So 3 Farms cost 4 Mt/month,
and 1 Farm, 1 House and 1 Mine costs 6 Mt, etc - this is arranged so as to
encourage specialisation. (But note that 1 Farm & 2 Mines is a self-supporting
arrangement, which provides a (meagre) supply of VTs and a slight excess
of Mts, for any Player who does not want to get involved in trading, but
still wants to be able to vote and pay eir rent.)

This is still an early draft - more an explanation of the idea than an 
actual proposal. We would appreciate any input on the following:

1) Plots as a currency - we want the number of Plots in the system to be
relatively constant, but we also need to provide new Players with Plots.
I do not want there to ever be any entity with a negative Plots holding.
The best way I can see to do this, is to work Plots like the Kudo system.
When a new player joins, 3 Plots are created & given to em. When e leaves
all eir Plots are destroyed. The problem is that this is scammable, by 
getting new players to join, transfer their plots to you, and then leave.

2) Timing of transfers & reporting, in order to streamline this as much 
as possible.

3) Tuning the economy

Constructive criticisms are very welcome.

------------

Create a rule titled "Plots" reading:

   Plots are a currency. The recordkeeper of Plots is the Cartographer.

   Whenever a Player joins the game for the first time, e recieves 3 Plots.

Create a rule titled "Material" reading:

   Material is a currency. The recordkeeper of Material is the Cartographer. 
   Material may be abbreviated as Mt.

   Whenever a Player joins the game for the first time, e recieves 10 Mt.

Each current player recieves 3 Plots and 10 Mt.

Amend rule 1710 by to read:

   There is an Office of Cartographor. The Cartographor recieves a salary 
   equal to 2 times the Basic Officer Salary.

   At least once each Nomic Week, the Cartographor shall post a Report to the 
   Public Forum containing the following information: 

    * all Locations, and which Locations are Adjacent to which others
    * the Location of all Entities that have a Location
    * all Movement since the previous report (if any)
    * the current status of all Plots in the game, and the changes (if any)
      since the previous report
    * the current status of all Material in the game, and the changes (if any) 
      since the previous report
    * the status of all Plots and Material possessed by all former Players
      at the time they left the game

Create a rule titled "Structures" reading:

   Each plot may have one Structure on it, or be empty. Only those Structures 
   exist which are defined in the rules. The Structure on a plot is part of
   that plot's status.

   The following Structures exist:
    * Farms
    * Churches
    * Mines
    * Houses

   A Player may build a Structure of eir choice on an empty Plot e possesses 
   by informing the Cartographor that e is building the Structure and paying 
   5 Mt, which are destroyed.

   A Player may tear down a Structure on one of eir Plots by informing the 
   Cartographor that e is tearing down the structure. When a Player tears 
   down a Structure, the Plot becomes empty, and 2 Mt are created and given
   to the Player.

Create a rule titled "Upkeep on Structures" reading:

   Each Structure requires an upkeep. The upkeep cost is 2 Mt for the first 
   Structure of each type that a Player owns, and 1 Mt for each additional 
   structure. The upkeep is paid automatically on the 1st of every month. 
   However, if a player does not have enough Mt to pay the upkeep on all of 
   eir Structures, e has one week to pay the upkeep on eir structures or 
   all of eir Structures collapse and are destroyed.

Create a rule titled "Production from Structures" reading:

   Structures may produce something each week. The production from Structures 
   takes place at the time of the Cartographor's weekly report. The items 
   produced by Structures are as follows:

    * Farms produce 5 VT
    * Houses produce 1 P-Note
    * Mines produce 1 Mt

   Churches do not produce anything. However, each Church is considered to 
   be two players for the purposes of randomly allocating Indulgences, and 
   any Indulgences which would be given to the Church are instead given to 
   the Church's owner.

   The Cartographor shall detect and report all currency transfers required
   by this rule.

Amend rule 833 by removing the text:

   At the end of the Voting Period for a Proposal, if a Proposal has received
   more FOR Votes than AGAINST Votes, the Payor for that Proposal gains a 
   number of P-Notes equal to the number of FOR Votes less the number of 
   AGAINST Votes.

   If, however, a Proposal has received more AGAINST Votes than FOR Votes, 
   that Payor loses a number of P-Notes equal the number of AGAINST Votes 
   less the number of FOR Votes.

   If the number of FOR Votes and AGAINST Votes are equal, the Payor neither
   gains nor loses P-Notes as a result of this Rule.

Repeal rule 947. [P-Notes for ruleset reduction]

Repeal rule 1705. [P-Notes for style]

Repeal rule 1684. [VT Supply]

