Proto: Unequal stipends to drive the economy

-----
Idea: In the Plots proto Blob and Antimatter want to create not only a
scarce supply of currency, but also an unequally distributed one, to
make the economy more interesting. 

However, they do more than that: they also introduce an economic
background simulation. This may be fun in itself, but seems to me very
much like MUDding (or playing a computer game like SimCity or
whatever) by hand.

While I fully support the first goal I don't feel like spending a lot
of time micromanaging my "real estate". This is a strategic problem in
game design (for example, a very important one for ConSims): do you
want it to be results oriented or simulation oriented? Both aspects
can be fun, but for the latter the paperwork must compare favorably to
the entertainment gained - in the case of the Plots proto I don't
think it does. 

So I would suggest the same incentive to trade currencies, and thus to
have more of an economy, can be introduced in a much simpler way if we
cut the simulation aspect and focus on the desired result: how to give
unequal amounts of currency to each player.

This proto would introduce a stipend of both P-notes and VTs as
(nearly ?) the only source of these currencies in addition to
officers' salaries. Inequalitiy is introduced by giving a much higher
stipend to players who "specialize" in one of the two currencies. On
the other hand, one can choose a small, but balanced income to avoid
trading (just as one can build 1 Farm & 2 Mines to be self-supporting
in the Plots proto).

I am sure the detailed amounts of income need a lot of finetuning - I
just lack the experience for this - comments anyone?. I have based my
first suggestion on the following estimate:

On average (over players and time), every player needs a little less
than one P-note per week, and about three VTs. (Dear assessor and
promotor, is that a good estimate in your experience?)

So we need to introduce 3*N VTs and N P-notes into the game each week,
where N is the number of active players. Roughly N VTs are given out
as salaries, the rest must come from stipends.

I did not want to make the stipends noninteger amounts of currency,
esp. as the MUQ for P-notes is one, so I decided to pay them only
fortnightly - this way more finetuning of the amounts is possible.

------
Proto:

Every two weeks every player receives a stipend of either VTs or
P-notes or both.

There are three types of stipend: balanced, VT only or P-note only. A
player must choose which type of stipend e wants to receive. This
choice can be changed by notifying ??; the change only becomes valid
four weeks after this notification.

After the adoption of this rule every player must make this choice for
the first time and notify ?? As Soon As Possible. Players who fail to
do so start with a balanced stipend. This paragraph will remove itself
10 days after the adoption of this rule.

A balanced stipend consists of 1 P-note and 4 VTs.
A VT only stipend consists of 9 VTs.
A P-note only stipend consists of 4 P-notes.

(Missing: who pays these?)

Amend rule 833 by removing the text:

   At the end of the Voting Period for a Proposal, if a Proposal has received
   more FOR Votes than AGAINST Votes, the Payor for that Proposal gains a 
   number of P-Notes equal to the number of FOR Votes less the number of 
   AGAINST Votes.

   If, however, a Proposal has received more AGAINST Votes than FOR Votes, 
   that Payor loses a number of P-Notes equal the number of AGAINST Votes 
   less the number of FOR Votes.

   If the number of FOR Votes and AGAINST Votes are equal, the Payor neither
   gains nor loses P-Notes as a result of this Rule.

Repeal rule 1684. [VT Supply]

------
Pro's: 

- Introduces the same effect (scarce and unequally distributed
currency incomes) as the Plots proto, but with much less paperwork
(especially for each player, but also for the officer(s) supervising
the stipends) 

- Changes and readjustments are easy to implement. For example it may
turn out that too few (or too many) units of one currency are
circulating. This would either stifle the game (or make the economy
ineffective in creating scarcity and trade). But a simple rule change
can adjust the income provided by stipends. Or an additional rule
could limit the overall circulation of some currency and raise taxes
to pay the stipends, as I suggested some time ago.

Adjustments like that would be much harder to implement in an economy
driven by private property like plots and production facilities;
changing their effectiveness would not only be more difficult than
changing stipends technically, it would also be frustrating for
players who invested a lot of effort into getting eir businesses
running.

Con's:

- We loose the fun and excitement of running an economy simulation
within Agora as a whole; individual players loose the possibility to
be proud owners of a well run business and trade organization.

- Whatever else you can think of.

Open questions:

- Who is responsible for paying the stipends and for keeping a list of
who gets which stipend? We could either introduce a new office for
this, or split the task: The assessor stays responsible for the VT
part of the stipends, the promotor for the P-notes.

- We may want to keep Rules 947 and 1705, after all. In an environment
of scarce P-notes they may even make more of a difference than
now. Then we would have some extra source for VTs (salaries) and for
P-notes(R 947 & 1705). The old main sources of VTs and P-notes from
Rule 1684 and 833 must be abolished, of course.

Remarks:

- It might be nice to change some officers' salaries to be paid in
P-notes to introduce some variety. On the other hand, then every
officer could collect eir salary in one currency and eir stipend in
the other, avoiding the need to trade. 

- Needs some technical polishing if Pragmatic Currencies go through,
of course.

I hope the developers and supporters of the Plots concept see this as
a constructive challenge, not as a personal attack on all the nice
toys they have devised (this is _not_ meant to sound ironic - I
have fiddled around with homemade economy simulations, too, and I
think I know how much fun - and work - it is).

Kolja A.

